oc:kn_47762485 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When rewriting any generic marketing or sales content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Brand voice enforcement replaces vague language ('I think', 'we are pleased', 'excited to announce') with specific data points, bold claims, and measurable outcomes." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Data-driven, confident voice attributes are consistently applied across all content types in the examples — generic hedging language is the primary anti-pattern to eliminate." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_6eb605fc a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When selecting tone parameters for enforcement" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Tone settings (formality, energy, technical depth) must be calibrated per content type: cold outreach is HIGH energy/MEDIUM formality/LOW technical depth; proposals are MEDIUM energy/HIGH formality/HIGH technical depth; Slack is MEDIUM energy/LOW formality." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Voice attributes are consistent across types, but tone sliders shift based on audience and channel expectations." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_797b9615 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing LinkedIn posts, social content, or announcements" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Avoid hype-driven language like 'revolutionary', 'game-changing', or 'change the way you work' — replace with measurable outcomes and specific numbers." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The brand voice is confident and data-driven, not hype-driven. Specificity builds more credibility than superlatives." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_8de85d69 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before using any example as a template" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Replace all fictional specifics (data points, product names, metrics) with data from the user's actual brand guidelines and context before applying examples." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Examples use a fictional B2B SaaS company for illustration only; real enforcement requires actual brand data." .

oc:kn_9208722e a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing follow-up emails or sequences" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never send empty follow-ups that merely say 'just following up' or 'checking in' — every touch must add new value (data, insights, benchmarks)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Empty follow-ups violate the 'data-driven' and 'confident' voice attributes and erode perceived expertise." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_d029c5f0 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing internal communications" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Internal communications (Slack, team messages) can be less polished but must still reflect brand voice attributes — direct, data-driven, approachable." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Brand voice applies everywhere; internal comms relax formality but retain core attributes." ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

oc:kn_d3d4070c a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When enforcing brand voice on any content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "When enforcing brand voice, match the content type to the closest example, note which voice attributes are most active for that type, apply tone settings, check 'We Are Not' boundaries, and verify terminology compliance." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Provides a repeatable calibration process that ensures consistent enforcement across content types." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

